Redefining what your happiness, home and heath looks like, takes a lot of courage.

Our brains are wired to choose the familiar, even if it’s not truly bringing us happiness, it doesn’t truly feel like home and it’s not fully healthy.

Our brains will always choose a familiar hell over an unfamiliar heaven.

To go against that and chose a better life for yourself takes a strength that many never muster.

Over my lifetime I’ve come to share so many stories and experiences with dog owners, dog trainers and women who have left domestic violence.

Many people may not ever find that courage to change their circumstance…

…but when they do. My god when they do, it’s so beautiful and awe inspiring to watch them flourish and thrive.

If you’ve left hard circumstances, if you’ve changed your idea of what happiness, love, home and healthy looks like - maybe no one has told you - but those who see you are so proud of you.

I’m proud of you.

I got my wisdom teeth out this past week.

(Picture totally unrelated I was just having a good lift today🤣🤌🏼)

Anyway, it got me thinking about how much being healthy isn’t always accessible.

I left home before I even graduated high school.

While my parents didn’t do the best job at raising a competent child that knew how to feed herself properly, I also didn’t grow up with a mother that emphasized the importance of really basic things (oral hygiene, washing your face, sunscreen, etc)

Luckily I figured those things out on my own with some help from mother figures along the way.

However, coupled with growing up poor, being technically homeless when I entered college, not having affordable access to healthcare nor the engrained importance of such things - I wasn’t living very healthy.

While I was afforded a lot of opportunity to learn and I just happened to make fitness a hobby, I was “healthy” in the sense that I learned how to exercise properly and how to feed myself with nutrition dense foods…there are a multitude of ways you can be healthy.

Having regular access to health care (dental, eyes and body) isn’t easy and often isn’t an option.

Oddly enough I found myself sitting in a dentist chair staring up at the TV mounted to the ceiling with an overwhelming feeling of…shame?

I felt like these people were going to judge me for how my teeth health may appear (surprisingly they said they’re actually pretty good all things considered - just need to floss more🫣)

Anyway, I feel like these are things rarely spoken about. I kinda wish I had seen someone somewhere talk about how hard it is to show up and do something you haven’t done in a long time. Maybe due to life circumstances, maybe not.

If you’ve gotten to the end of this dear reader, and a part of this has resonated with you and you can think to something in your life you’ve put off because you feel a bit embarrassed, ashamed or guilty - I hope you’re able to gather courage and do what’s best for your health.

It was hard and it was scary, I don’t think I’m alone in being nervous to go to the dentist, but your health is WORTH IT.

Also grateful for wife perks of insurance😂

You are so busy looking at the trees, you miss the forest 🌲

I’ve always loved this idiomatic phrase.

There are several variations, but they all convey the same message:

🌼You are so focused on the details that you miss the bigger picture.

I know I have a tendency to do this, maybe you do too.

Perfectionist tendencies?
Empathic tendencies?

Maybe both?

It’s not a fear of failure, as I have always embraced mistakes and failures - they have been my biggest teachers.

No, I think not.

It’s the frustration I’m trying to avoid.

I lean towards perfectionism because I will avoid the frustration of having to go back to the beginning and start over.

Yes, I will take many lessons and learn a lot but that doesn’t take away the frustration.

My strong emotional connection to all of that which surrounds me (maybe why I always play a shaman or similar figures in games🤣) pushes me to yearn towards not frustrating those around me - as I feel it acutely.

And so…I miss the forest.

Because I’m so busy looking at a tree.

Letting go, letting things flow and taking gratitude or appreciation to zooming out and seeing the magnificence that surrounds me.

The life I’ve built. The life of those around me. The beauty that surrounds me. The blessings bestowed upon me.

So, if you’ve gotten to the end of this dear reader, zoom out for a second.

Maybe life has been challenging and in some regard has left you hardened.

But for a moment, just a moment, zoom out and appreciate the forest. Don’t focus on the trees ♥️🌲

Weightlifting mistakes you could be making👇🏽

I’m not a coach but I’ve been lifting weights in the gym since 2011, so I have a few things I’ve picked up. I’m sure to this day I still make mistakes and things could be tweaked, so don’t mistake this for me being up on a high horse. I want to share what I’ve learned and wish I knew earlier because I could of made progress so much faster.

👉🏽 Mistake 1) Ego Lifting

Probably the roots cause of most mistakes made. 

Weightlifting isn’t about the number.

It’s about the amount of control and ability to do the purpose or function of the exercise under a certain amount of weight/tension or stress.

The number is merely an indicator or a way for you to track and monitor your progress.

It’s not impressive slapping 45s onto something if you can’t control it, isolate the movement or do the purpose of the exercise.

The very definition of “just because you can doesn’t mean you should”

👉🏽Mistake 2) Missing the Purpose of the Exercise

Exercising and doing weightlifting is only as beneficial to the degree of which you understand what you’re trying to accomplish.

Common place this is seen?… Bicep Curls.

Lotssss of swinging. Which misses the purpose. If you can’t isolate the movement and not engage other muscle groups, you’re not actually benefiting your biceps. You’re working out your shoulder.

👉🏽Mistake 3) Hunching, Neck Arching, and General Form

This is usually a side effect of the other two mistakes. 

No depth on squats or bench, neck arching or back hunching on deadlift, jerking around weights using momentum on pull downs or rows, swinging on bicep curls, etc.

Filming your exercises helps a lot to allow you to see where you could be making these mistakes!

I highly recommend doing research on what muscle group you should be activating during an exercise and ensuring that it’s the only one you feel while performing.

Any other mistakes you commonly see or you yourself have done? (Because all these examples were from my personal experiences I used to do😅)

It’s odd how time, and therefore inherently age, gives you a deeper love for yourself.

Youth is fraught with insecurities, comparing and doubts about who you are, what you look like, your perception to others and much more.

But there’s something that settles in you as you get older and you find your true self, true purpose and a contentment within you.

At least that’s what age as provided for me.

Perhaps it’s the maturity and stability of those around me, the different types of people I surround myself with that has helped in this change.

The people around me don’t care about social media. They don’t care about how the outside world perceives them. They don’t care about the followers, the numbers, the frivolous pressures of society. They’re genuine, unique and authentic in all interactions. No posturing for others, trying to perform as tho they are something they are not.

It’s calming.

Soothing.

Secure.

To be settled.
To be confident in who you are.
Most importantly who you are not.
And deciding on who you will become.

Some may look ahead and see age as something to rial against.

But I choose to love this life and embrace it with open arms, not clenched fists at my side.

How will you choose to love yourself over the passage of time?

The first picture: a deeply broken girl who finally- for the first time - found a thread to hold onto. A girl who was secretly abused at home by her boyfriend. Physically, financially, emotionally and mentally. Isolated. Depressed. Anxious. Desperately trying to keep it a secret because of deep embarrassment. She was trying to find a will to live. No one cared for her. No one would believe her.

The second picture: a woman strong and independent that has learned how to trust again and no longer feels that she HAS to be strong and independent. A now married woman who can be soft and feminine. Able and willing to be cared for and provided for.

Today I turned over the keys to this house. The house that was a symbol for so much and what I needed at the time. I healed a lot here. I reforged myself here.

I had been putting off going through all of my old possessions that were moved into the back of a closet and never touched.

Lots of memories were in boxes and bags.

It was cathartic to go through, acknowledge the memories, and let them go. To even throw almost everything away.

When I found this bag of my ex’s things my first thought was to find a lighter to burn all of it to ash.

Alas, I couldn’t. So I put them where they best belonged.

I’m not one for rituals or superstitions but I do believe that karma comes around. So I put a note into a mirror and tossed it with the rest of his things to seal his karmic fate.

I wrote another note and burned it.

“I am free of you and any negative intention from you or others”

When I burned it, all that remained were the words

“I am free”

To those who went through deep trauma, especially over years, know that your feelings of pain, grief, betrayal and CPTSD don’t shrink. They don’t go away.

You just grow larger around it. And one day you are so much more than that abuse that you are free.

I’m so blessed to be able to look back and know… 

I am free.

Sometimes it’s hard to see the changes - the small subtleties day in and day out. Being so close to the picture.

Zooming out isn’t always easy.

Being able to stay in close and mind the details, while simultaneously looking at the whole picture is the plight we as humans have.

Not just with fitness.

With health, mindset, relationships, career and so much more (like dog training for example lol)

Sometimes it’s a positive!

Suddenly seeing the weight you’ve lost or muscle you’ve put on when it feels like you’ve made no progress at all because you see yourself in the mirror several times a day.

You become somewhat blind.

Same goes in the opposite direction. Suddenly finding yourself in an abusive relationship, waking up one morning and wondering “what happened? How did I get here?”

Maybe a job you slowly come to despise. Debt you suddenly wrack up or waking up wondering how you’ve become overweight and out of shape.

It’s the inability to be zoomed in on the details while simultaneously seeing the whole picture zoomed out.

If you’ve been zoomed in, zoom out today. Congratulate yourself on your progress.

If you’ve been zoomed out, zoom in today. Congratulate yourself on your progress.

Both are important for our wellbeing, happiness and our ability to grow, thrive and prosper🌻

2 of the most shocking parts i had to accept about fitness influencers online:

1) most women had breast implants
2) most men (of course someone women too) were on enhancement drugs

If you’re not somehow connected to the health and fitness industry by someone close, then you’ll probably end up like I was feeling…like I could never look like the women I saw online.

I want to be extremely clear here: there is NOTHING absolutely nothing wrong with breast augmentation if that is what you choose to do with your body. I am specifically pointing out MY own insecurities, specifically NOT body shaming anyone.

I want to point out that many people (myself included) are naive to what enhanced bodies look like when first following “fitness” people online.

And when those enhanced bodies push you to buy certain workout programs, supplements, diets, etc with an underlying message of “if you buy this you’ll look like me too” 

…well that’s a problem.

Because unless you are also going to go and get breast implants and then diet down to a very low body fat percentage plus probably work with a professional coach - you’ll be hard pressed to look like them by just buying their workout guide.

Let’s be honest, extremely low body fat percentage without breasts isn’t going to look as appealing on stage or on social media unless you have breasts (which lets all remember that breasts are made up of primarily body fat).

I’m not a man or have used enhanced drugs so I can not speak to that experience.

So, treat yourself kindly when you’re scrolling TikTok or instagram and see these wonderfully fit women that still have a womanly shape and think to yourself “I wish I could look like that” because the chances are high that they have had surgery done to augment their body.

Thanks for still reading if you’re at this point in my caption.

I hope I could give you a little piece of mind I wish I had realized when I first came into the health and fitness space.

Love,
Your Online Big Sister ♥️🫶🏼

I find it harder during winter months to get super hype for the gym😅 it’s cold, typically not as bright and sunny outside and did I mention it’s cold?

Recently I’ve been really focusing on my hip health.

I took at long trip up to New York to meet with my consulting client and between the different bed, sitting on a plane and sitting in cars - my hips weren’t happy.

It led to really aggravating lower back pain.

What’s “fixed” it was consistently releasing my psoas and piriformis.

Alongside dying glute and hip flexor isolated exercises.

If you too struggle with some hip or lower back pain, I’d encourage you to:

- Implement hip and glute exercises

- Release your psoas (personally I don’t like the pso right, it’s too big for me, I got glute blade and it’s dramatic to say but it’s changed my life lol)

- Release your piriformis

- Have an adequate and we’ll rounded warm up routine before hitting a lift

Happy lifting!
Xoxo - Nat♥️

If I were to tell someone how to get fit and healthy from ground zero this is what I would say:

I’d probably tell them to learn how to read nutrition labels.
Understand what a serving size of certain foods and liquids look like.

I’d probably tell them to research about the importance of fats and carbs. How there’s a difference between ‘good’ and ‘bad’ fats and a difference between simple and complex sugars and carbs.

I’d probably tell them that whenever possible, try and cook your own meals and use real ingredients. Try and limit fake sugars.

I’d probably tell them to get some resistance bands off of Amazon and practice their form at home. I’d tell them to record their form and compare it up against professionals they admire online to ensure they’re lifting with proper form.

I’d probably tell them to get into a routine they can stick to before trying to get a gym membership and buy a whole bunch of stuff and change too many aspects of their life before they can even commit to a 20min workout at home.

I’d probably tell them that consistency looks different day to day. And if you skip a day with your fitness or with your nutrition to not “throw the baby out with the bath water”

I’d probably tell them to write out a lifting plan, ensuring to incorporate compound lifts (squat, deadlift and bench) and maybe to structure their lifts by:
- Push day 
- Pull day
- Leg day (quads, hamstrings, glutes)
- Push/Pull day
- Cardio and abs
- 2 rest days

I’d probably tell them to left with weight that allows for good form and full range of motion instead of trying to ego lift a bunch of weight with shitty form.

I’d probably tell them to prioritize sleep, good sleep, and to try and find ways to healthy cope with stress/anxiety (yes, this means break up with your shitty boyfriend)

And finally I would tell them to change their lifestyle. That it’s not a question of “am I going to go to the gym today?” It’s always “what time am I going to the gym today?”

It’s not “should I eat non-processed foods today?” It’s “what non-processed foods will I eat today?”

But uh yeah, that’s just me and if someone asked what I would tell them!

Xoxo
